text: I can't wait until the movie where all of the heroes in the movies will come together.  Since all of these movies are leading up to the Infinity Wars, you know it will happen.  It has to since the Infinity Stones we know of all scattered and being contained in different places with the Power Stone being held by Nova Corps, Asgard having the Space Stone, Vision getting his power from the Mind Stone, Doctor Strange having access to the Time Stone and the Collector holding the Reality Stone (we don't know where the Soul Stone is at, but I have a feeling The Vulture will have it in Spider-Man: Homecoming since one of The Vulture's abilities was to drain people's lifeforce, which is something the Soul Stone would obviously be able to do).  And in the end, Thanos will have to begin an invasion to obtain each one, and as we saw in Avengers: Age of Ultron, he's pretty much on the prowl.  So in the end, all of the heroes in these will obviously have to come together.  It wouldn't be a connected universe if it didn't happen (then again, there's no chance of seeing the Netflix heroes or Ghost Rider from Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. coming in, so that does kind of suck).

text: Say what you will, but I enjoyed this movie from start to finish. In the first film, we were introduced to the Guardians of the Galaxy with these bright and colorful characters, worlds beyond imagination, and a story that sets as an introduction so memorable. With the second film, we got a story that furthers the adventures of our favorite characters. We got some more funny moments, plus character development from certain characters if you've seen the film. Plus, I found the villain a lot interesting as Marvel Villains go. The story gets even darker, but at the same time, it keeps you enlightened. Our fav characters are still here we love it. Plus, BABY GROOT EVERYBODY!!!!!!! Personally speaking, I loved this film as it is.

Props to marvel studios, that's all i have to say...

author: Alan Ulm

text: My quick review: This is nowhere near as good a movie as Guard of Galaxy 1. Some of the visuals are even better than part 1. The first half of the movie dragged on. The main problem was the dialogue was a lot of bathroom humor and goofy bad jokes (and I know this franchise is supposed to have some goofy humor, but it was wayyy overdone) Some of the jokes, and I could care less about censorship or adult humor, were downright disgusting, as in gross. The second half had some excellent action scenes but the action scenes in part 1 seemed better choreographed or something. I would rate it a C+ or B- and part 1 I would give an A. Plot and characters were all over the place. Even for a purposefully light funny and goofy action movie, the jokes mostly fell flat. Worth seeing but nowhere near as cohesive as part 1. Dialogue in action sci fi and comic book movies seems to be getting more and more off-the-wall and silly every year. Every scene does not have to be a snappy dumb one-liner. What happened to serious dialogue?

text: Ok, people. I'm just now able to watch this film , and only 10 mins into this flick I'm struck by some very original (very effective) directorial choices that are delighting me to no end. So,, if the rest of this james gunn film is as excellent as the first film and this first sequence of the sequel, why on any planet did "the internet" act as interested and excited as an involuntary hooker when the film was available for wide-release (and reviews)?    Maybe, I'm just becoming old-man-who-shakes-fist-at-clouds after the e-vandalism that delights in slagging films like the last jedi in the same way as idiot teens we used to think it was funny to drive around and try to knock mailboxes down with a base-ball bat?  Cause,inexplicably, everyone was "in the mood" to yuck it up for ragnarock....folks, if you are part of this new activism fad that groupsources ways to make good films (or any films) bomb simply for the kicks it gives you...you are creating an artificial-market that will cause a similar reaction to a false market that happened just before marvel went bankrupt, who knows what DC did, and all the comic-book store owners lost the businesses they had invested all they had to live in....economics 101.....ok, im gonna watch the rest of guardians 2, and if it's great, I will know a group of people who have been warned what happens to fun things when people play dirty and just want the other team to fail more than they want the entire industry to win....and i will shake myfist at the clouds as well.   sincerely, your friendly hometown et carter   020718
